South Africa has recorded 7 070 new cases in the last 24-hour cycle, taking the total number to 1 430 648. The country has also recorded 753 new COVID-19 related fatalities on Wednesday. In a statement, Health Minister Dr Zweli Mkhize says most of the new deaths were recorded in Kwa-Zulu Natal. “Regrettably, we report 753 more COVID-19 related deaths: 6 from Eastern Cape, 17 from the Free State, 75 from Gauteng, 261 from Kwa-Zulu Natal, 219 from Limpopo, 16 from Mpumalanga, 50 from North West, 7 from Northern Cape and 102 from the Western Cape,” says Dr Mkhize.  This brings the total number of deaths to 42 550. Recoveries currently stand at 1 263 478. The cumulative number of tests conducted to date is 8 107 833. As of today, the total number of confirmed #COVID19 cases is 1 430 648, the total number of deaths is 42 550 and the total number of recoveries is 1 263 476. pic.twitter.com/pNCTGUnOe3 — Dr Zweli Mkhize (@DrZweliMkhize) January 27, 2021 